  "footnotes": [
    "Attila's capital (c.445–453 CE): Attila's court was located on the Great Plain near the Tisza River; the Hunnic 'Ring' treasury (reportedly enormous) was looted by Charlemagne after destroying the Avar Khaganate, which occupied the same territory and may have inherited Hunnic wealth",
    "Avar Khaganate (568–804): the Avars occupied the Carpathian Basin for over two centuries, raiding Byzantium and Frankish kingdoms repeatedly; Charlemagne's destruction of the Avars in 791–796 and dismantling of their ring-fortress treasury is one of the great medieval military campaigns",
    "Magyar Conquest (895–896): the seven Magyar tribes under Árpád crossed the Carpathians and settled the Pannonian Basin, displacing or absorbing Slavic and remnant populations; Stephen I's 1000 CE coronation (with a papal crown from Sylvester II) anchored Hungary in Latin Christendom",
    "Mongol invasion (1241–1242): the Mongol force under Batu Khan and Subutai annihilated the Hungarian army at Mohi and depopulated much of the Great Plain; they withdrew only when news of the Great Khan Ögedei's death required return to Mongolia; Hungary lost perhaps 20–50% of its population",
    "Battle of Mohács (1526): the decisive Ottoman victory over Louis II of Hungary ended the independent medieval kingdom; Hungary was divided into three: Ottoman-occupied central Hungary, the Habsburg 'Royal Hungary' in the northwest, and the semi-autonomous Principality of Transylvania in the east — a partition that lasted 173 years",
    "Treaty of Trianon (1920): Hungary lost two-thirds of its pre-war territory, including Transylvania (to Romania), Slovakia (to Czechoslovakia), and Croatia-Slavonia (to Yugoslavia); the trauma of Trianon remains central to Hungarian national consciousness and politics"
  ]
